ğŸ“˜ Problem Statement

John is building a binary tree where nodes are inserted based on user input.
The tree inserts elements level-wise at the next available position.
The program keeps accepting integer inputs until -1 is entered.
After constructing the binary tree, the program prints the post-order traversal of the tree.


---

ğŸ“¥ Input Format

The input consists of space-separated integers representing the data to be inserted into the binary tree.
The input terminates when -1 is entered.


---

ğŸ“¤ Output Format

The output prints the post-order traversal of the binary tree.
All values are printed in a single line separated by spaces.


---

ğŸ“Œ Code Constraints

1 â‰¤ data â‰¤ 100



---

ğŸ§ª Sample Test Case 1

Input

5 6 7 8 9 -1

Output

8 9 6 7 5


---

ğŸ§ª Sample Test Case 2

Input

1 7 9 5 6 -1

Output

5 6 7 9 1


---

 C++ Code 

#include <iostream>
#include <queue>
using namespace std;

struct Node {
    int data;
    Node* left;
    Node* right;
};

Node* root = nullptr;

Node* createNode(int d) {
    Node* newNode = new Node();
    newNode->data = d;
    newNode->left = nullptr;
    newNode->right = nullptr;
    return newNode;
}

void append(int d) {
    Node* newNode = createNode(d);
    if(root == nullptr) {
        root = newNode;
        return;
    }
    queue<Node*> q;
    q.push(root);
    while(!q.empty()) {
        Node* temp = q.front();
        q.pop();
        if(temp->left != nullptr)
            q.push(temp->left);
        else {
            temp->left = newNode;
            return;
        }
        if(temp->right != nullptr)
            q.push(temp->right);
        else {
            temp->right = newNode;
            return;
        }
    }
}

void postorder(Node* root) {
    if(root == nullptr)
        return;
    postorder(root->left);
    postorder(root->right);
    cout << root->data << " ";
}

int main() {
    int d;
    do {
        cin >> d;
        if(d > 0)
            append(d);
    } while(d != -1);
    postorder(root);
    return 0;
}
